{
 "_meta": {
  "what": "Curated CPU model-string -> spec lookup table for the deterministic description extractor (app/services/desc_extractor/cpu.py). Keys are NORMALIZED model strings exactly as the cpu grammar emits them (uppercase; 'E5-2650L V4', 'GOLD 6248', 'I7-9700K', 'EPYC 7551P'). Values hold only the six seeded cpu facet keys: family, socket, core_count, clock_speed_ghz (base clock), tdp_watts, architecture.",
  "provenance": "Hand-curated 2026-06 from public Intel ARK / AMD product-spec knowledge for the highest-volume server/desktop models in the SFDC CPU corpus (source_ingest/analysis/CPU_DECODE_FEASIBILITY.md): Xeon E5-1600/2600/4600 v1-v4, Xeon Scalable gen1/gen2 (Bronze/Silver/Gold/Platinum), common E3/E7, EPYC 7001/7002, common Core i3/i5/i7/i9 desktop. A field is present ONLY when stated with high confidence; uncertain fields are omitted per model (e.g. EPYC 7001 configurable 155/170W TDPs, E7 socket naming). Several entries are corroborated by verbatim corpus descriptions (E5-2673 V3/V4, GOLD 6134, E3-1225 V5, I5-8400, I7-9700K).",
  "extending": "Extend, don't trust blindly: add models only with a primary source (Intel ARK / AMD spec page) in hand; clock_speed_ghz is the BASE clock, never turbo; keep keys in the extractor's normalized form; every value must stay inside the seeded cpu enum/range vocabulary in app/data/commodity_seeds.json (drift-guarded by tests/test_desc_extractor_routing.py). Desc-stated tokens always override this table (merged UNDER extracted values in extract_cpu)."
 },
